{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Bring fresh, cold water to a boil in a kettle. Once boiling, remove from heat and let it sit for 30 seconds. The ideal temperature is around 200°F, just off the boil.",
      "title": "Heat Your Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Measure 30 grams of whole coffee beans on a kitchen scale. This makes about two cups. If you don't have a scale, use 4 tablespoons of beans.",
      "title": "Measure the Beans"
    },
    {
      "text": "Grind the beans on a coarse setting until they look like coarse sea salt. Avoid a fine grind, as it will slip through the filter and make your coffee gritty.",
      "title": "Grind the Beans Coarsely"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour a small amount of hot water into your empty French press, swirl it around, then dump it out. The press should feel warm to the touch.",
      "title": "Preheat the French Press"
    },
    {
      "text": "Add the ground coffee to the empty French press. Give it a gentle shake to level the grounds evenly across the bottom.",
      "title": "Add Coffee Grounds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour 500 grams (about 2 cups) of hot water over the grounds. Pour in a steady, circular motion to saturate all the coffee. You'll see a foamy layer called the bloom form on top.",
      "title": "Pour the Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use a spoon to gently stir the grounds into the water, breaking up the bloom. Stir for about 5 seconds until the surface looks even.",
      "title": "Stir the Bloom"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the lid on the French press with the plunger pulled all the way up. Set a timer for 4 minutes and let the coffee steep undisturbed.",
      "title": "Steep for Four Minutes"
    },
    {
      "text": "When the timer goes off, press the plunger down slowly and steadily. It should take about 20 seconds to reach the bottom. If you feel strong resistance, pull up slightly and try again.",
      "title": "Plunge Slowly"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the coffee into your mug immediately. Don't let it sit in the press, or it will keep brewing and turn bitter. Enjoy your fresh French press coffee!",
      "title": "Pour and Serve"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Pick a spot that gets at least 6-8 hours of direct sunlight per day. Mark the bed area, about 3 feet wide and 4 feet long per tomato plant.",
      "title": "Choose a Sunny Garden Spot"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pull out weeds, rocks, and old roots from the bed by hand or with a hand trowel. The surface should look clean with only bare soil visible.",
      "title": "Clear Debris and Weeds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push a garden fork or spade 12 inches deep into the soil. Lift and turn it across the entire bed until the soil feels loose and crumbly.",
      "title": "Loosen the Soil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Take a small handful of damp soil and squeeze it. If it crumbles when poked, it's ready. If it stays in a sticky ball, wait a day and test again.",
      "title": "Test Soil Moisture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use a soil pH test kit from a garden store. Tomatoes thrive at pH 6.2-6.8. Follow the kit instructions and read the color result.",
      "title": "Check Soil pH"
    },
    {
      "text": "If pH is below 6.2, sprinkle garden lime per package directions. If above 6.8, mix in elemental sulfur. Rake it lightly into the top 4 inches.",
      "title": "Adjust pH if Needed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Spread a 3-inch layer of finished compost evenly across the bed. The surface should look dark and fluffy with no bare soil showing through.",
      "title": "Spread Compost on Top"
    },
    {
      "text": "Sprinkle a balanced organic fertilizer like 5-10-10 across the bed, following the bag's rate (usually 1-2 cups per 10 square feet).",
      "title": "Add Balanced Fertilizer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use a garden fork to mix the compost and fertilizer into the top 6-8 inches of soil. Work back and forth until everything blends into a uniform texture.",
      "title": "Mix Amendments Into Soil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Drag the back of a rake across the bed to smooth and level the surface. The top should look flat and free of large clumps.",
      "title": "Rake the Bed Smooth"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use a hose with a gentle shower setting and water until the top 6 inches feel moist. Push a finger in to check — it should feel like a wrung-out sponge.",
      "title": "Water the Bed Deeply"
    },
    {
      "text": "Let the bed rest for 7-14 days before planting. This allows amendments to integrate and soil microbes to activate. The soil is now ready for tomato seedlings.",
      "title": "Let the Soil Settle"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Lay your fabric flat on a large clean surface. Smooth out any wrinkles with your hands. The fabric should lie completely flat with no folds or bumps.",
      "title": "Prepare Your Work Surface"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place your pillowcase pattern on top of the fabric. Position it so the grain line arrow runs parallel to the fabric's selvage edge.",
      "title": "Position the Pattern"
    },
    {
      "text": "Grab your measuring tape and confirm the pattern dimensions match your pillow size. A standard pillowcase needs a piece measuring 20 by 32 inches. Adjust placement if needed.",
      "title": "Check the Measurements"
    },
    {
      "text": "Mark the cutting lines on the fabric using tailor's chalk. Trace around the entire pattern edge. You should see a clear chalk outline when you lift the pattern slightly.",
      "title": "Mark the Cutting Lines"
    },
    {
      "text": "Insert straight pins through the pattern and fabric every 4 to 5 inches. Place pins perpendicular to the edge so you can easily remove them while cutting.",
      "title": "Pin the Pattern in Place"
    },
    {
      "text": "Run your hand across the pinned fabric to check for puckers or shifts. If the fabric bunches anywhere, remove that pin and re-pin it flatter.",
      "title": "Smooth and Double-Check"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pick up your fabric scissors and cut along the chalk line in long, smooth strokes. Keep the fabric flat on the table—lift the scissors, not the fabric. Cut just outside your marked line.",
      "title": "Cut Along the Lines"
    },
    {
      "text": "Carefully remove each pin and set them in your pin cushion. Lift the pattern away from the fabric piece.",
      "title": "Remove the Pins"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hold up your cut fabric piece and compare it to the pattern. The edges should be clean and straight, with no jagged sections. You now have a fabric piece ready to sew.",
      "title": "Verify Your Cut Piece"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Sit in a quiet space with your guitar resting on your lap. Make sure your tuner is nearby or open a tuning app like GuitarTuna on your phone.",
      "title": "Prepare Your Space and Tuner"
    },
    {
      "text": "Clip a digital tuner to your guitar's headstock, or place your phone close to the soundhole if using an app. Turn the tuner on. You should see a display showing note names.",
      "title": "Attach or Open Your Tuner"
    },
    {
      "text": "Hold the guitar so the thickest string is on top. The strings from thickest to thinnest should read: E, A, D, G, B, E. This is standard tuning.",
      "title": "Identify the Six Strings"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the thickest string (6th string) with your thumb. Watch the tuner display. It should read close to *E*. If it shows a different note, you'll adjust next.",
      "title": "Pluck the Low E String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the tuning peg for the 6th string slowly. If the note reads flat (below E), tighten the peg. If sharp (above E), loosen it. Stop when the tuner shows E and the needle sits in the center.",
      "title": "Tune the Low E String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 5th string and check the tuner. Adjust its peg until the display reads *A* with the needle centered. Pluck again to confirm it holds steady.",
      "title": "Tune the A String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 4th string. Turn its tuning peg until the tuner shows *D* in the center. Re-pluck if the note fades before the tuner locks on.",
      "title": "Tune the D String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 3rd string and adjust its peg until the tuner reads *G* with a centered needle. Take your time—small peg turns make big pitch changes.",
      "title": "Tune the G String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 2nd string. Turn the peg until the display shows *B* and the needle is centered. This string is thinner, so turn the peg gently.",
      "title": "Tune the B String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the thinnest string (1st string). Adjust its peg until the tuner reads *E*—one octave higher than the 6th string. Turn very slowly; thin strings can snap if overtightened.",
      "title": "Tune the High E String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck each string one more time from low E to high E. The tuner should show each correct note with a centered needle. If any string drifted, fine-tune it again.",
      "title": "Recheck Every String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Strum all six strings together. The chord should sound bright and harmonious. If it sounds off, repeat the recheck step. Your guitar is now in standard tuning—ready to play!",
      "title": "Strum to Confirm"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Turn on your camera and rotate the mode dial to **M** for full manual control. You should see M displayed on the top screen or LCD.",
      "title": "Set Camera to Manual Mode"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look through the viewfinder or at the LCD. Find the exposure meter — a scale from -2 to +2 with a moving indicator. Aim to center it at 0 for balanced exposure.",
      "title": "Locate the Exposure Meter"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the **ISO** button and set it to 100 for bright outdoor scenes or 800 for indoor light. Lower ISO means less grain. Confirm the new value appears on screen.",
      "title": "Set Your ISO First"
    },
    {
      "text": "Rotate the aperture dial to choose your f-stop. Use `f/2.8` for blurry backgrounds or `f/8` for sharp landscapes. Watch the aperture value update on your display.",
      "title": "Choose Your Aperture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the shutter speed dial while watching the exposure meter. Adjust until the indicator sits at **0**. Use `1/125` or faster for handheld shots to avoid blur.",
      "title": "Adjust Shutter Speed to Balance"
    },
    {
      "text": "Frame your subject and press the shutter button halfway. Check the meter — if it shows +1 or higher, the image is too bright; -1 or lower means too dark.",
      "title": "Half-Press to Meter the Scene"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the shutter fully to capture the image. Review it on the LCD. The photo should show detail in both shadows and highlights, not pure black or white areas.",
      "title": "Take a Test Shot"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the **DISP** or **INFO** button to display the histogram. A good exposure shows data spread across the graph without tall spikes pushed against the left or right edge.",
      "title": "Check the Histogram"
    },
    {
      "text": "If the image is too dark, slow the shutter speed or widen the aperture by one stop. If too bright, do the opposite. Take another shot and recheck the histogram.",
      "title": "Fine-Tune and Reshoot"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Find a clear area with enough room to extend your arms forward. Remove any obstacles around you. You should have at least 3 feet of space in every direction.",
      "title": "Clear Your Space"
    },
    {
      "text": "Stand tall with your feet shoulder-width apart. Point your toes slightly outward, about 5-15 degrees. Your weight should feel evenly distributed across both feet.",
      "title": "Set Your Stance"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pull your shoulders back and down, away from your ears. Lift your chest slightly. Tighten your core as if bracing for a light punch to the stomach.",
      "title": "Engage Your Core"
    },
    {
      "text": "Raise both arms straight out in front of you at shoulder height, palms facing down. This counterbalance will help you stay upright during the squat.",
      "title": "Position Your Arms"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look at a spot on the wall directly in front of you at eye level. Keep your gaze there throughout the movement. Your neck should feel relaxed, not strained.",
      "title": "Fix Your Gaze"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push your hips back as if reaching for a chair behind you. Start the movement from your hips, not your knees. You should feel your weight shift toward your heels.",
      "title": "Initiate the Hinge"
    },
    {
      "text": "Bend your knees and lower down slowly. Track your knees in line with your toes—don't let them cave inward. Keep your chest lifted as you descend.",
      "title": "Lower with Control"
    },
    {
      "text": "Stop when your thighs are parallel to the floor, or as low as you can go with good form. Your heels should stay flat on the ground. Pause for one second at the bottom.",
      "title": "Reach Squat Depth"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press through your heels and stand back up. Drive your hips forward at the top, but don't lock your knees. Squeeze your glutes when you reach the standing position.",
      "title": "Drive Back Up"
    },
    {
      "text": "Perform 5 squats slowly, focusing on each cue. If you wobble or feel pain in your knees, reset and try again. Smooth, controlled reps mean your form is working.",
      "title": "Complete 5 Practice Reps"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Separe 500g de farinha de trigo, 10g de fermento biológico seco, 10g de sal, 15g de açúcar, 300ml de água morna e 30ml de azeite. Tenha também uma tigela grande e uma superfície limpa para sovar.",
      "title": "Separe os Ingredientes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Aqueça 300ml de água até ficar morna ao toque, cerca de 35°C. Teste com o dedo: deve estar confortável, nunca quente. Água muito quente mata o fermento.",
      "title": "Aqueça a Água"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em uma tigela pequena, misture a água morna com 15g de açúcar e 10g de fermento. Mexa levemente e aguarde 10 minutos. Uma espuma cremosa deve se formar na superfície, indicando que o fermento está ativo.",
      "title": "Ative o Fermento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em uma tigela grande, coloque 500g de farinha de trigo e faça um buraco no centro. Adicione 10g de sal nas bordas da farinha, longe do fermento, pois o sal pode prejudicar a fermentação se tocar diretamente.",
      "title": "Prepare a Farinha"
    },
    {
      "text": "Despeje a mistura de fermento ativado no centro da farinha e adicione 30ml de azeite. Misture com uma colher ou as mãos até formar uma massa pegajosa e disforme. Não se preocupe com a aparência ainda.",
      "title": "Combine os Ingredientes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Polvilhe farinha em uma superfície limpa e transfira a massa para ela. Comece a sovar empurrando com a base das mãos, dobrando e girando. A massa estará grudenta no início, isso é normal.",
      "title": "Transfira para a Bancada"
    },
    {
      "text": "Sove por 10 minutos contínuos, empurrando, dobrando e girando a massa. Adicione pouquíssima farinha se grudar demais. A massa deve ficar lisa, elástica e soltar das mãos.",
      "title": "Sove a Massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Estique um pequeno pedaço da massa entre os dedos. Se formar uma película fina translúcida sem rasgar, está pronta. Se rasgar facilmente, sove por mais 2-3 minutos e teste novamente.",
      "title": "Teste a Elasticidade"
    },
    {
      "text": "Modele a massa em uma bola lisa, puxando as laterais para baixo. A superfície deve ficar tensa e brilhante. Sua massa está pronta para a próxima etapa de fermentação.",
      "title": "Forme uma Bola Lisa"
    }
  ]
}

