{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Clear a large, flat workspace and gather your case, motherboard, CPU, RAM, storage, GPU, PSU, and a Phillips screwdriver. Touch a metal surface to discharge static electricity before handling components.",
      "title": "Prepare Your Workspace"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the motherboard on top of its anti-static bag. Lift the CPU socket lever on the motherboard. The socket cover will release as you raise it fully.",
      "title": "Open the CPU Socket"
    },
    {
      "text": "Align the gold triangle on the CPU corner with the triangle on the socket. Gently lower the CPU straight down. It should drop in without force. Lower the lever to lock it in place.",
      "title": "Install the CPU"
    },
    {
      "text": "Apply a pea-sized dot of thermal paste to the center of the CPU if your cooler doesn't have pre-applied paste. Align the cooler over the CPU and secure it with screws or clips. Plug its fan cable into the CPU_FAN header.",
      "title": "Mount the CPU Cooler"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open the clips on both ends of a RAM slot. Align the notch on the RAM stick with the notch in the slot. Press down firmly on both ends until the clips snap closed. Use slots 2 and 4 for dual-channel.",
      "title": "Install the RAM"
    },
    {
      "text": "Locate the M.2 slot on the motherboard. Remove the mounting screw. Insert your M.2 SSD at a 30-degree angle, then press it flat and secure with the screw. It should sit snugly against the board.",
      "title": "Install the M.2 SSD"
    },
    {
      "text": "Install the I/O shield into the back of the case by pressing it in from inside until it clicks. Lower the motherboard onto the standoffs, aligning ports with the I/O shield. Secure with screws in all mounting holes.",
      "title": "Mount Motherboard in Case"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the power supply into its bay, typically at the bottom rear of the case. Position the fan facing down or out as your case allows. Secure it with four screws from outside the case.",
      "title": "Install the Power Supply"
    },
    {
      "text": "Connect the 24-pin cable to the long motherboard connector. Connect the 8-pin CPU power cable to the top of the board near the CPU. Both cables should click firmly into place.",
      "title": "Connect Power to Motherboard"
    },
    {
      "text": "Release the PCIe slot clip and remove the corresponding case slot covers. Align the GPU with the top PCIe x16 slot and press down until it clicks. Secure it to the case with screws. Connect PCIe power cables from the PSU.",
      "title": "Install the Graphics Card"
    },
    {
      "text": "Connect SATA cables from any 2.5-inch SSDs or hard drives to the motherboard SATA ports. Plug SATA power connectors from the PSU into each drive. Mount drives in the case bays using screws or tool-less trays.",
      "title": "Connect Storage Drives"
    },
    {
      "text": "Plug the tiny power switch, reset, HDD LED, and power LED connectors into the front panel header. Check your motherboard manual for pin layout. Connect USB and audio cables to their labeled headers.",
      "title": "Wire Front Panel Connectors"
    },
    {
      "text": "Route cables behind the motherboard tray where possible and secure with zip ties. Double-check that every component has power and data connections. Close the side panels once everything looks tidy.",
      "title": "Tidy Cables and Close Case"
    },
    {
      "text": "Connect a monitor, keyboard, mouse, and power cable. Press the power button. Fans should spin, lights should turn on, and you should see the BIOS screen or boot logo. Your computer is assembled.",
      "title": "Power On and Verify"
    }
  ]
}
